<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-009-037 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 522 082</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  Nov 21 1991 n1809* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (UK) 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM is poised to cut a further 20,000 jobs.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Personnel management).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Labor CostsPersonnelJob SecurityWork Force Reduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>IBM IS POISED TO CUT A FURTHER 20,000 JOBSandM;Next month IBM is expected to announce that a further 20,000 jobs will go ontop of the 20,000 it has already cut.andP;  This will bring IBM's total number ofemployees down to around 330,000 worldwide at the end of 1992, from about373,000 at the start of this year and from 407,000 at IBM's peak in 1988.andP;  Asyet nobody seems sure how IBM will make those job cuts as it has a traditionof no layoffs and has always said that layoffs would be a real last resortmeasure.andP;  Most onlookers reckon that IBM will continue with voluntaryprogrammes encouraging employees into accepting early retirement or buy-outpackages.andP;  Nevertheless, as time has gone on these voluntary packages havebeen getting less generous offering more stick and less carrot.andP;  Another ployit may use is to increase its standards for employee performance - a moveexpected to lead to a much higher rate of firings.andP;  That IBM is considering afurther bloodletting seems to indicate that the company expects its positionto remain difficult even though it is at the beginning of a new mainframeproduct cycle.andO;</TEXT></DOC>